What is R?

  • Open source statistical programming language, runs on Windows-MAC-Linux/Unix
  • A collaborative effort
    • many people contribute
    • to include a package first we need to install the package
  • Download R

R packages

  install.packages("package-name")
  library("package-name")
  • Install the package only once, but you have to include it every time you start R
    • to view the version of R and the packages you already included
  sessionInfo()
  • You want to contribute? Build a package and upload it to Comprehensive R Archive Network, CRAN

RStudio environment

  • R is a command line scripting language
  • RStudio provides a GUI for R
    • makes it convenient to work with R
    • Everything is organized, at your finger tip
    • Specially very convenient to create dynamic documents
  • Download RStudio

Modes of data in R

  • numeric
  • character
  • logical
  • factor
  • ordered
  • complex
  • raw
  • NULL

How do you get the mode?

mode(5+3i)
## [1] "complex"

Checking and changing the mode

x <- "5.42"
is.numeric(x)
## [1] FALSE
y <- as.numeric("5.44")
mode(y)
## [1] "numeric"
is.logical(FALSE)
## [1] TRUE

R data structures

Notice the coercion

x <- c(1,2,3)
x
## [1] 1 2 3
y <- c(1,2,"3")
y
## [1] "1" "2" "3"
mode(y)
## [1] "character"

Vectorized calculations

  • Functions work on the whole structure
  • Try not to use loops.
x <- rep(1:3,2)
x
## [1] 1 2 3 1 2 3
x+4
## [1] 5 6 7 5 6 7
sum(x^2)
## [1] 28


y <- matrix(1:9, ncol = 3)
y
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    4    7
## [2,]    2    5    8
## [3,]    3    6    9
# elementwise operation
y/y
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    1    1
## [2,]    1    1    1
## [3,]    1    1    1

Quiz: y/c(1,2,3) =?

Do it yourself

x <- 1:3
y <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)
z <- c("A","B", "C")

What values are returned for the following commands?

x+y
x*y
c(x,z)
c(y,z)

Reproducible reports using R

  • Is that how you prepare data analysis report?
  • What if we have to do it again and again
  • What if the data changes or part of the data changes
  • What if we can do everything from one place

How can we do this from R?

  • Wonderful R packages knitr and rmarkdown
  install.packages("knitr" "rmarkdown")
  library("knitr", "rmarkdown")
  • Install the packages only once, but you have to include it every time you start R
  • Its free

Creating a Markdown (.Rmd) file

  • Open a new R Markdown file to start

  • The new file will start with a complete template

  • Compile (knit) the file from RStudio tool bar

  • You can create (knit) it as HTML, word document as well as pdf

Markdown (.Rmd) example

R code chunk

Showing a table of data

  • Use function kable() to display a table of data
knitr::kable(head(mtcars, 10))
  • Javascript library datatable helps us to generate enhanced table using package DT. This feature is available for HTML output only.
DT::datatable( head(iris, 12),
  fillContainer = FALSE, options = list(pageLength = 6)
)

Showing equation

$$f(x) = \frac 1{\sqrt{2\pi \sigma^2}}e^{-\frac 1 {2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2}$$

will produce

\[f(x) = \frac 1{\sqrt{2\pi \sigma^2}}e^{-\frac 1 {2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2}\] We use single $ to write equation inline such as (\(\sigma^2\)) and double $$ to write equation as above.

What can you do?

  • You may generate periodic reports
    • generate templates, so everyday the same report is updated based on new data
  • Share the report online as HTML report within your intranet secure network
    • create interactive dashboard to produce customizable report.
    • create a repository of previous data analysis report for other employees to review, use and learn.
  • Any other ideas?
